7","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","England":"Anglie","deane, Bedfordshire, England":"Dean, Bedfordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1495–":"1495–Afdød","1498–Female":"1498–Afdød","1517–Female":"1517–Afdød","1518–Female":"1518–Afdød","1520–Female":"1520–Afdød","1523–Female":"1523–Afdød","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1495–Male":"1495–Afdød","1495":"1495","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1518":"1518","1517":"1517","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","England":"England","deane, Bedfordshire, England":"Dean, Bedfordshire, England"},"nl":{"1495–":"1495–Overleden","1498–Female":"1498–Overleden","1517–Female":"1517–Overleden","1518–Female":"1518–Overleden","1520–Female":"1520–Overleden","1523–Female":"1523–Overleden","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1495–Male":"1495–Overleden","1495":"1495","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1518":"1518","1517":"1517","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","England":"England","deane, Bedfordshire, England":"Dean, Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"1495–":"1495–Deceased","1498–Female":"1498–Deceased","1517–Female":"1517–Deceased","1518–Female":"1518–Deceased","1520–Female":"1520–Deceased","1523–Female":"1523–Deceased","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1495–Male":"1495–Deceased","1495":"1495","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1518":"1518","1517":"1517","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","England":"England","deane, Bedfordshire, England":"Dean, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dillingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): habitational name, probably from Dullingham in Cambridgeshire, recorded as <i>Dolingeham</i> in 1214 and <i>Dillyngham</i> in 1298, named in Old English as ‘homestead (Old English <i>hām</i>) of the people (<i>-inga-</i>) of Dull(a)’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Arthur","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin.  King Arthur  was a British king of the 5th or 6th century, about whom virtually no historical facts are known. He ruled in Britain after the collapse of the Roman Empire and before the coming of the Germanic tribes, and a vast body of legends grew up around him in the literatures of medieval Western Europe. His name is first found in the Latinized form <i>Artorius</i>; it is of obscure etymology. The spelling with <i>-th-</i> was popular among the gentry families of West Yorkshire in the late 1400s, even before  Henry VII , who may have hoped to capitalize on the legend, gave the name to his son. It remained in regular use in some areas and its popularity exploded in the early 19th century, largely as a result of the fame of  Arthur Wellesley  (  1769–1852 ), Duke of Wellington, the victor at the Battle of Waterloo and subsequently prime minister. Further influences were  Tennyson's  Idylls of the King (  1859–85 ), and the widespread Victorian interest, especially among the Pre-Raphaelites, in things medieval in general and in Arthurian legend in particular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":54,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":63,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":74,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":92,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":105,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Arthur Dillingham was born in 1495, in England. He married Rosanna in 1516. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 4 daughters."},"et":{"1495–":"1495–Surnud","1498–Female":"1498–Surnud","1517–Female":"1517–Surnud","1518–Female":"1518–Surnud","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1523–Female":"1523–Surnud","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1495–Male":"1495–Surnud","1495":"1495","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","